STAT5003Stage2

1 Overview of the problem

COVID-19 has had a huge impact on the global airline industry. As the coronavirus pandemic is coming to an end, airline companies need to work hard to revive their business. To help the airline industry, our group did some experiments to find out the most important features that impact passengers satisfaction. We utilized a dataset called Airline Passenger Satisfaction[1], which contains an airline passenger satisfaction survey. Since the response variable, Satisfaction, is separated into two categories, this problem can be defined as a binary classification problem.

2. Dataset description

After combining the train set and the test set into one, the dataset has 129,880 rows and 23 columns. The response variable, Satisfaction, has two levels, including neutral or dissatisfied and satisfied. As the percentages of the two target classes are quite similar (with 43.4% for satisfied and 56.6% for neutral or dissatisfied), the dataset is relatively balanced. Except for the response variable, there are 3 numeric variables and 19 categorical variables. The 3 numeric variables are Age, Arrival.Delay.in.Minutes, and Departure.Delay.in.Minutes. Also, we made some pictures to describe the distribution of Age, Flight.Distance and Travel.Type, and Class by satisfaction level.

dftrain <- read.csv("train.csv")

4. Feature selection

Feature engineering includes addressing missing values, removing outliers and reduce dimensions to improve the performance of classifiers.

Checking any imbalance issue in the dataset: The dataset is relatively balanced with the neutral or dissatisfied class being 13% higher than the satisfied class. Rather than balancing our dataset to 50:50, we decided to adding Recall, Precision and F-1 score evaluation metrics on top of the accuracy metric, so that the classifiers performance exploring on this relatively balanced data can be better evaluated.

Encoding categorical variables: We encode categorical variables differently for feature in ordinal nature and in nominal nature. For ordinal nature feature, such as Class, we encode it, where 0 represents Eco class, 1 represents Eco plus class and 2 represents Business class. while other categorical variables were encoded by dummy variables with 0 and 1.

Dimensionality reduction:

class <- df[["satisfaction"]]
num.dat <- df %>% select(!satisfaction)
pca_res <- prcomp(num.dat,scale=TRUE,center = TRUE)
cproportion <- cumsum(pca_res$sdev^2 / sum(pca_res$sdev^2))
# Forward Stepwise selection
set.seed(31)
inTrain <- createDataPartition(df$satisfaction, p = 0.5)[[1]]
train <- df[inTrain,]
test  <- df[-inTrain,]
cls.train <- df$satisfaction[inTrain]
cls.test <- df$satisfaction[-inTrain]

selectFeature <- function(train, test, cls.train, cls.test, features) {
  current.best.accuracy <- -Inf
  selected.i <- NULL
  for (i in seq(ncol(train))) {
    current.f <- colnames(train)[i]
    if (!current.f %in% c(features,"satisfaction")) {
      model <- train(satisfaction ~ .,
                     data = train[,c(features,current.f,"satisfaction")],
                     method ="glm", family = "binomial")
      Pred <- predict(model,newdata = test[,c(features,current.f,"satisfaction")])
      test.acc <- sum(Pred == cls.test) / length(cls.test)

      if (test.acc > current.best.accuracy) {
        current.best.accuracy <- test.acc
        selected.i <- colnames(train)[i]
      }
    }
  }
  return(c(selected.i,current.best.accuracy))
}

features <- NULL
accuracy <- NULL
# select the 1 to 17 best features using knn as a wrapper classifier
for (j in 1:22) {
  res <- selectFeature(train, test, cls.train, cls.test, features)
  selected.i<-res[1]
  current.best.accuracy<-res[2]
  print(c(selected.i,current.best.accuracy))
  features <- c(features, selected.i)
  accuracy <- c(accuracy,current.best.accuracy)
}

FeatureSelection <- data.frame(Features=features,
                               Accuracy=accuracy)
write.csv(FeatureSelection,"FeatureSelection.csv")
FeatureSelection <-read.csv("FeatureSelection.csv")
Acc<- FeatureSelection[['Accuracy']]
write.csv(FeatureSelection,"FeatureSelection.csv")

There is no perfect multicollinearity issue as no coefficient exactly equal to 1. So we did not remove any feature based on the correlation. We apply the principal component analysis (PCA) to reduce the dimensionality. From the elbow plot we can discover that 17 features capture 95% principal component. However, there are not dominant features in the principle components, which doesnt show a good separation between two clusters and isnt interpretable enough. So we perform forward stepwise feature selection to select 17 best features using logistic regression as a wrapper classifier. From the accuracy graph, we can see that when number of features is over 17, the accuracy doesnt seem to improve much. And we also need to consider that we may lose information that can be used by some ensemble methods if we drop some features, so we finally select 17 features.

Logistic regression is a technique used in machine learning to assess the likelihood of something by finding solutions to problems with binary (0 or 1) answers. First, because our project is a binary problem, the only possible classifications are satisfied, and neutral or satisfied. Second, the Logistic Regression model is simple to comprehend, and it offers a great deal of interpretability. The relative weights of the various features provide insight into the influence those features have on the overall outcome. Logistic Regression is a model that is considered to be reasonably straightforward and fundamental, which is why we have chosen to utilize it as our baseline model. Finally, there are many available numerical optimisation methods that can be used to determine the ideal answer, and the training speed is rapid.

When developing the model, the initial step was to determine which combination of the hyperparameters alpha and lambda produced the best results. We tried a variety of different combinations with alpha = 0 and 1 and lambda = 0, 0.1 and 1, and in the end, we came to the conclusion that the accuracy of the model of hyperparameter combination is highest when alpha = 1 and lambda = 0. This also indicates that there is no penalty in the Logistic Regression model. The fitted model makes use of the glm() function, with the family parameter set to binomial. This indicates that the connection function is logit, which is shorthand for logistic regression. The resampling technique for repeatedcv is defined by trControl as part of the list of parameters for the function that will be executed; number = 10 and repeats = 3 signifies that the number of iterations (CrossValidation) should be repeated three times, followed by 10 folds of resampling. Our logistic regression model produced an accuracy value of 0.8738 and a Kappa value of 0.7418 as its final result.

5.2 GBM: Gradient Boosting

# 10 fold cross validation with 3 repeats
train_control <- caret::trainControl(method = "repeatedcv", number = 10, repeats = 3)

library(gbm)
gbmGrid = expand.grid(
   n.trees = c(100,500,1000) # iterations
  ,interaction.depth = c(1,2,6,9)
  ,shrinkage = 0.1 # learning rate
  # This default uses very slow learn rates for small data sets and uses 0.1 for all data sets with more than 10,000 records.
  ,n.minobsinnode = c(3,5,10)
  )

set.seed(5003)
fit_gbm = train(satisfaction~., data = train[,c(selected,"satisfaction")], method="gbm", trControl=train_control,tuneGrid = gbmGrid,metric = "Accuracy", verbose=FALSE)

fit_gbm

library(gbm)
best_gbmGrid = expand.grid(
   n.trees = 1000
  ,interaction.depth = 9
  ,shrinkage = 0.1
  ,n.minobsinnode = 5
  )
gbm.start<-Sys.time()
best_gbm = train(satisfaction~., data = train[,c(selected,"satisfaction")], method="gbm", trControl=train_control,tuneGrid = best_gbmGrid,metric = "Accuracy", verbose=FALSE)

Mat_gbm

fit_gbm$bestTune

Gradient Boosting is a type of ensemble machine learning algorithm that can be used for classification predictive modelling problems. Here, we chose this model because it is effective and often a key algorithm utilized to win machine learning competitions (like Kaggle) on tabular data. While Basic Gradient Boosting can overfit a training set quickly, Stochastic Gradient Boosting can benefit from a regularization that introduces randomness and reduces the correlation between the trees. Thus, the issue of overfitting can be solved. In this algorithm, a base learner should be fitted on a randomly selected (without replacement) subsample of the training data at each iteration. With this minor modification, the performance of gradient boosting can be improved a lot.

To improve the accuracy of the algorithm when specifically working for our dataset, we need to tune hyperparameters. There are only four hyperparameters that can be configured in this algorithm: n.trees, interaction.depth, shrinkage, and n.minobsinnode. The parameter n.trees refers to the number of trees or iterations in the model. Although larger numbers of trees can help to reduce the training error, it would lead to overfitting if set too high. The parameter interaction.depth refers to the number of leaves or the maximum depth of each tree. The order of approximation can be restricted by setting up the tree depth. According to previous work, the default six-node tree appears to do an excellent job. The parameter shrinkage refers to the learning rate of the model. In GBM, shrinkage is used to reduce the impact of each additional fitted tree. When lambda is as small as possible, the model can be improved by taking many small steps so that the negative impact of any boosting iteration can be corrected in subsequent steps. The parameter n.minobsinnode refers to the minimum number of samples in a trees terminal nodes. This number should be set lower if the training set is small.

Since our dataset has more than 100,000 records, we set the learn rate to 0.1 first. Then, by using the method of 10 fold cross validation with 3 repeats, we tested the number of iterations with 100, 500, 1000, the maximum depth of each tree with 1, 2, 6, 9, and the minimum number of observations in the trees terminal nodes with 3, 5, 10. The model performs best when n.trees equals 1000, interaction.depth equals 9, and n.minobsinnode equals 5. Finally, we got the highest accuracy of 95.59% and the kappa statistic of 91.73%.

Category Gradient Boosting (Catboost) is another variation of the gradient boosting algorithm with an efficient implementation. It also has some advantages, such as improved computational speed and support for categorical input variables. The trees in CatBoost are balanced, which means that the splitting condition must be consistent across all nodes at the same depth. This symmetric tree architecture can help prevent overfitting and accelerate evaluation. The splitting condition in CatBoost is determined by using a greedy method to choose the split that results in the smallest penalty from a list of possible feature-split pairs assigned to the leaf as the split. Catboost is an ordered boosting method that increases robustness to unseen data.

We focus on fine tuning six model parameters: depth, learning_rate, iterations, 12_leaf_reg, rsm, and border_count to improve accuracy, speed, and prevent overfitting. The parameter depth refers to the depth of a tree, which controls the complexity of the model. The parameter learning_rate refers to the learning rate for reducing gradient steps. This parameter is used to prevent overfitting. The parameter iterations refers to the number of trees. Tuning this parameter can improve the computational speed. The parameter 12_leaf_reg is a regularization, which also benefits on controlling overfitting. The parameter rsm refers to a random subspace method, which is a fraction of the number of features used in a split selection. This is a parameter that works for faster speed. The parameter border_count refers to the number of splits for numerical features. This is also a parameter that slightly impacts the speed of training on the CPU.

In our experiment, we configured depth as 1 and 10, learning_rate as 0.01 and 0.1, iterations as 50 and 200, 12_leaf_reg as le-3 and 3, rsm as 1, and border_count as 64 and 128. Then, we use 10 fold cross validation with 3 repeats again to find out the combination of parameters that results in the best performance. The highest accuracy is 96.23% and the highest kappa statistic is 92.3%, with depth equals 10, learning_rate equals 0.1, iterations equals 200, 12_leaf_reg equals 3, rsm equals 1, and border_count equals 64.

Nave Bayes is a classical supervised machine learning algorithm that is used to do classification work. It is based on the Bayes Theorem as well as the idea that each variable in the model is independent of the others. However, the predictor variables cannot be absolutely independent of each other in the real world. Since Nave Bayes considers there are no correlations between the predictor variables, it is called Nave. This logic might have some negative impact on the accuracy of the machine learning model. Although it is often outperformed by other classifiers, Nave Bayes can work fast and scale well, and has good performance on many classification problems.

Here, we use the klaR package to build a Nave Bayes classifier. This model has three hyperparameters to tune: fL, usekernel, and adjust. The parameter fL refers to the factor of Laplace correction, which is used to incorporate the Laplace smoother. The bigger the Laplace smoothing value, the more the models are made the same. The parameter usekernel refers to a choice of using the kernel density estimate for continuous variables or a gaussian density estimate. When using the klaR engine, the usekernel is set to TRUE by default. The parameter adjust helps to control the bandwidth of the kernel density. The larger value of the engine argument adjust means a more flexible density estimate.

Again, we applied the 10 fold cross validation with 3 repeats to select the best Nave Bayes model parameters, with fL set to 0, 0.1, 1, 5, usekernel set to TRUE, FALSE, and adjust set to 0.1, 1, 5. We found that the highest accuracy always occurs when userkernel is set to TRUE and adjust equals 1, no matter how fL is configured. However, this zero-probability event does not mean an impossible event. Thus, the final values used for the model are: usekernel equals TRUE, and adjust equals 1. The accuracy of the best model reaches 89.33%, with a kappa statistic of 78.4%.

5.5 Random Forest

library(randomForest)
library(ggplot2)
set.seed(5003)
rf.acc.test<-c()
for (i in c(seq(from=50,to=150,by=50),seq(from=200,to=1200,by=200))){
  randomforest.model<-randomForest(satisfaction~.,data=train[,c(selected,"satisfaction")],ntree=i)
  randomforest.pred<-predict(randomforest.model,newdata=test[,c(selected,"satisfaction")])
  test.acc<-sum(randomforest.pred==cls.test)/length(cls.test)
  rf.acc.test<-c(rf.acc.test,test.acc)
}

rf.acc.test1<-c(rf.acc.test)
ntree1<-c(seq(from=50,to=150,by=50),seq(from=200,to=1200,by=200))
randomforest.df<-data.frame(ntree1,rf.acc.test1)

library(ggplot2)
ggplot(randomforest.df,aes(x=ntree1,y=rf.acc.test1))+geom_point()+geom_line()+ggtitle("Relationship between ntree and accuracy")+xlab("number of trees")+ylab("accuracy")+theme_bw()

A random forest, in its most basic form, is a forest that has been constructed in an arbitrary fashion using numerous different decision trees, and none of which are connected to one another in any manner. When a new sample is input after a forest has been obtained, each decision tree in the forest will make a determination, classify the category (for the purpose of a classification algorithm), and then compare which category is judged to be the most prevalent in order to determine which category the sample belongs to. For more precise, Random forests are a classification approach that are utilized as part of an ensemble. The development of decision trees based on the provided training data and the comparison of these to the test data are both included in the technique. When solving a classification problem, statisticians turn to random forests to determine the relative relevance of the various factors[2]. In this particular project, random forest is a fantastic choice for us since it can manage the enormous quantity of data to classify them and minimize the dimensionality without us having to conduct any feature selection.

We have about 1300000 data in total, and 17 features. At the same time, it is able to figure out which features are the most important, how different features interact with one another, and prevent overfitting. For model building, we mainly used the RandomForest library, and the selection of the appropriate number of decision trees, or tuning of the random forest model, is the component of the model that bears the heaviest weight in terms of significance. First, by examining the line plot depicting the relationship between the number of decision trees and the accuracy (shown in the above), we can plainly see that the accuracy reaches its highest point when ntree = 600. As a result of this, when we were developing the model, we settled on the number of decision trees to be equal to 600. We are ecstatic in the final confusion matrix that obtains a satisfactory result for the random forest, which is accuracy of 0.9614 and Kappa of 0.9211.

The plot on the top left compares the classification accuracy rates on the test dataset. Apparently, the ensemble methods, including gradient boosting, catboost and random forest, outperforms that of the others. Catboost method gained the highest than the others at 96.23% whereas logistic regression had the lowest accuracy rate at 87.38%.

Although our dataset is relatively balanced, the negative class is still 13% higher than the positive satisfied class. So we also used recall, precision and f1 score metrics. Ensemble methods are again much higher than logistic regression and Nave Bayes in each metric. The distribution of all metrics are similar, indicating our more or less imbalanced dataset indeed does not affect the result.

Comparision of ROC curve:

We have also plotted the Receiver Operating Characteristics curve. The higher the area under the curve, shorting for AUC, the better the model is capable of distinguishing between classes. Again, ensemble methods resulted in much higher AUCs at around 0.96 than that of logistic regression at around 0.8691 and nave_bayes at 0.8939. Overall, ensemble methods outperform logistic regression and nave bayes. This may be because they combine multiple models and boost better overall accuracy compared to a single algorithm.

Models = c("Logistic Regression","Naive Bayes","Random Forest","Gradient Boosting","CatBoost")
Time = c("2 min","7 min","3 min","48 min","12 min")
table1 = data.frame(Models, Time)
table1

The running time on the test data for Gradient Boosting is the slowest at around 48 minutes, but for the other two ensemble methods, the running time is much better, with CatBoost at 12 minutes and Random Forest at only 3 minutes. Nave Bayes and logistic regression also performed well in running time.

Amongst all ensemble methods, random forest outperforms all the others. Gradient boosting has the slowest running time. Catboost has only 0.1% higher accuracy rate but much slower running time than the random forest. Thus random forest with hyper - parameter of ntree equals to 600, achieving 96.14% accuracy rate and 3 minutes running time on the test dataset, outperforms the others and is highly recommended to be used in our project.

The preceding plot of feature importance reveals that online boarding, flight.wifi.service, class, type.of.travel, and leg.room.service are the top five features in terms of importance for the random forest model, which is also our best model, when it is being trained for classification. The relevance of Feature importance is not only to inform us about which features are vital, but also to increase the quality of services that airlines may deliver based on these top rated features, hence enhancing passenger pleasure. For example, fine-tuning and upgrading the online boarding system, or increasing the stability and speed of the airlines wifi, may increase passenger satisfaction with their journey.

7. Conclusion

Limitations: In the feature selection section, less features can be selected to compare with 17 features resulting from PCA at 95%. Besides, due to the constraint of computational complexity and large data size, classifiers such as SVM can not be trained; besides, some hyper-parameters are hardly to be tuned.

Future works: In future works, firstly, we can try other feature engineering methods and train and test our dataset for less features and compare whether there is a considerable decrease in the accuracy rate. Besides, other hyper parameters are also worth to be tuned when we have a better computer hardware environment.
